	<p>Shepard Associate Master<br />
	Professor, Electrical Engineering and Computer Science<br />
	associatemaster@shepardrc.com</p>
	<div class="aspacer"></div>
</div>

<p>Larry Birnbaum is co-director of the Intelligent Information Laboratory, and teaches courses in the Medill/McCormick Center for Innovation in Technology, Media and Journalism. He received his doctorate in computer science from Yale University in 1986, and joined the Northwestern faculty in 1989. His research in artificial intelligence and computer science includes natural language processing, case-based reasoning, machine learning, human-computer interaction, educational software and computer vision.</p>
<p>Professor Birnbaum has been featured in the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/11/business/computer-generated-articles-are-gaining-traction.html">New York Times</a> for his work with computer-generated news articles. </p>

<div class="profile">
	<img src="<?php echo $html_htdocs; ?>images/profiles/assistant.jpg" width="137" height="180" />
	<name><strong>Elliot Mercer</strong></name>
	<p>Shepard Assistant Master<br />
	  Ph.D. student in Northwestern&rsquo;s Interdisciplinary Theatre &amp; Drama<br />
	assistantmaster@shepardrc.com</p>
	<div class="aspacer"></div>
</div>

<p>I hail from the San Francisco peninsula, where I grew up being forced to play outside in an ever-present fogbank. In high school I decided to pursue a career in dance, and at age sixteen I packed up and moved away to a boarding school for the arts in a small town named Idyllwild, which is perched in the middle of the woods, high atop an isolated mountain in Southern California. Known for attracting a diverse collection of international young artists and budding eccentrics, Idyllwild was very influential in fostering my love for all things experimental, avant-garde, and creatively bizarre.&nbsp; </p>
  <p>I began dancing professionally shortly after graduating high school and finished my undergraduate work through a unique program for professional dancers run by St. Mary's College of California. I then moved on to do an MA in Performance Studies at NYU before arriving in Chicago in 2012 to continue my graduate work as a PhD student in the Interdisciplinary Program in Theatre & Drama. I am studying the history of dance notation systems as well as the process of documenting and reconstructing dances. At Northwestern I teach both theatre and dance, and center most of my coursework on experimental art and performance from the 1960s and '70s. I encourage you all to come join my classes, as we explore all the weirdness, retro-kitsch, and “what-the-what?” that makes up this wonderfully peculiar time. </p>
<p>Having spent many years in ballet, I am also a sucker for fairy tales, cheesy romances, and stories that make little to no sense. I continue to believe that all emotions can be conveyed through simple hand gestures and that everything always ends happily ever after, even if you are turned into a swan, fall in love with a life-sized doll, or are imprisoned in a magical castle by a man named Kashchei the Immortal.</p>
  <p>I am very much looking forward to meeting you!</p>
</div>
<div id="right2">
<h5>What do masters do?</h5>
<p>The Master is a senior faculty member who "guides the intellectual and programmatic life of each residential college." For example, he coordinates fellows' participation in an undergraduate research grant called the <a target="_blank" href="http://undergradresearch.northwestern.edu/research-opportunities/residential-college-fellow-assistant-researcher-award-fara">FARA</a>. Learn more about the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.northwestern.edu/residentialcolleges/masterstaff/index.html">Master staff</a>.</p>

<p>The Associate Master shares the responsibilities with the Master.</p>

<p>The Assistant Master is a graduate student who helps with administrative duties, like organizing cross-RC events. They are usually awesome.</p>
</div>